  <static seed="1059" source="PCC-ORCCA-ed3/BasicAlgebra/QuadraticApplications/FlyingObjectApp30.pg">
    <statement><p>A remote control aircraft will perform a stunt by flying toward the ground and then up. Its height, in feet, can be modeled by the equation <m>h={1.4t^{2}-14t+40}</m>, where <m>t</m> is in seconds. The plane <ul form="popup" name="AnSwEr0001"><li>
<p>?</p>
</li><li>
<p>will</p>
</li><li>
<p>will not</p>
</li></ul> hit the ground during this stunt.</p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\text{will not}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To determine whether the plane will hit the ground, we substitute <m>h(t)=0</m> into <m>h(t)={1.4t^{2}-14t+40}</m>, and solve the equation by the Quadratic Formula:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{
        \begin{aligned}
            t \amp  = \frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}\\
              \amp  = \frac{-({-14})\pm\sqrt{({-14})^2-4(1.4)({40})}}{2(1.4)}\\
                   \amp  = \frac{{14}\pm\sqrt{{196}-{224}}}{2.8}\\
                   \amp  = \frac{{14}\pm\sqrt{{-28}}}{2.8}\\
                  
        \end{aligned}
     }</m></p>
<p>Since the equation has no real solution, the plane will not hit the ground during the stunt.</p>
</solution>
